      "id": "9778e422064ba3d8",
      "text": "> Caution is called for in making claims to autonomy, especially for a field of social reality that one is used to observing in relations of dependency. The burden of justification is considerable, especially since only recently a status nascendi at best has been diagnosed for this field. Thus Niklas Luhmann writes with regard to social work1 that the \"resource dependence of these efforts ... is so strong [that] one can doubt whether a social subsystem has already formed or whether it is a matter of widely scattered efforts at the level of interactions and organizations. It is clearly recognizable that it is no longer about caritas or about caring for the poor in the sense of tradition, but about efforts to bring about structural changes (keyword: help for self-help). Perhaps here we can consider a functional system in the making\" (Luhmann 1997a, 632f.). With this form of thematization, therefore, the empirical evidence of the phenomenon of social work is not questioned, as far as the levels of interaction and organization are concerned. Only the claim on the societal level remains controversial. And with that the level of the analysis to be done here is marked out; it has to be located on the level of a developed social theory. For this purpose, systems theory will be used here, which provides a conceptual toolkit for finding a constructive solution to the task at hand.\n"
