    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "74ff9ffb1b35d4ae",
      "text": "Such problem constructions exist in the meantime (Baecker 1994; Fuchs/ Schneider 1995). They can be related, in a dendend form, to a problem of modern society, which arises from its form of differentiation itself and from its effect on the scheme of inclusion and exclusion (Luhmann 1994; Stichweh 1988; Fuchs/Buhrow/Kriiger 1994; Fuchs/Schneider 1995). The underlying assumption is that the system of society, by switching from a stratified order to functional differentiation, has to reorganize the problem of inclusion/exclusion of persons (Fuchs 1997a). If all social functions, which have been served in the strata so far, are delegated to autonomously operating functional systems (such as economy, law, politics, education, art, science, etc.), then it follows that inclusion (participation) of all persons in all functional systems has to be guaranteed (Fuchs 1996). There is therefore an equality enforced by the form of differentiation itself, which is the equality of an opportunity (not of a reality), the equality of a knowledge. And what becomes problematic then is not the case that there is inequality (it is foreseen and must be tolerated in the core area of functional differentiation) (Fuchs 1999c), but only that the opportunity for equality of inclusion is not guaranteed. The stimulability of inequality in modern society thus does not refer to factual inequalities, but to a disbalancing of opportunities, which then makes it possible to sue for re-balancing in the form of claims and claim filiations, so to speak."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "d309dd56c541d00a",
      "text": "[…] The thesis is that the mere disbalancing of inclusion opportunities then turns into the systematic prevention of these opportunities, into a blockade of the possibility of general inclusion. This happens when (due to whatever causalities) exclusions affect a majority of functional systems, when, for example, a disability minimizes inclusion in the economy, largely excludes chances of participation in the intimate system, delays school careers or makes them impossible, in short, when a social address arises that is defective or damaged in this sense, which in more and more respects no longer benefits from general inclusion or is decisively threatened not to be able to benefit in the future."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "dd26b77c59b10600",
      "text": "What is decisive is that the form of functional differentiation forces the chance of general inclusion and thus at the same time throws up the chance of generalizing exclusion. In this sense it is diabolical. Built into the form itself is the inevitability of producing damaged addresses and the inevitability of having to avoid just such addresses. Or in other words: Modern society has to do at this point with a principled (argen) indeterminacy, with a paradox of: It cannot be, what cannot be!, but it is, what cannot be. \n\nSince paradoxes typically paralyze only observers (only for them there are paradoxes), it is to be expected that evolution (which does not know indeterminacies, it is not an observer) generates forms at this problem, which an observer can call a instead, and the assumption is that the differentiation of a system of social work realizes exactly this instead, i.e. performs the function of staging chances of re-inclusion for damaged addresses."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "c0a2d60f88c6bf8c",
      "text": "But it is precisely here that it is advisable to be very precise. Such a system cannot enforce the chance of general inclusion for society, because it is itself only a subsystem among other subsystems, and it cannot include for the functional systems, let alone: force them to inclusion in any form. Its function would be precisely located at the generation or re-generation of the chance of inclusion, and even more precisely: at the generation of the condition of the possibility of this chance. This is, as will quickly be seen, a double modalization: the generation of the possibility for a possibility."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "69c80a3ade242ddf",
      "text": "The unity of the system, in terms of function, would be at the level of this double modalization, which excludes the direct intervention of inclusion/exclusion. The system does not perform re-inclusion, it works on the restitution of the chance of a chance, and exactly in this it is functional for a form of society that is dependent on the possibility of general inclusion and cannot (may not) simultaneously see that processes of generalizing exclusion become possible on the diabolical opposite side."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "5ffd9a1ccdbb297f",
      "text": "[…] Thus, when we talk about defective, damaged addresses, we are not yet talking about damaged individuals, but about structures of communication. Re-inclusion (in the sense of this double modalization) then refers to what one could loosely call the tuning of social addresses, as a dressing that makes the chance for chance more probable or sometimes (as in the case of the severely disabled) opens it up in the first place. Social work is accordingly, and strictly speaking, work on social addresses and not: work on people, as formulations suggest that speak of people-processing systems. It is not about changing individuals. It is, one would think, excluded not only from logical but also from ethical considerations. Instead, the system reorganizes addressability."
    },
