      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "2ee3c0bd20b64785",
      "text": "[…] It is at this level of reality that it is determined what is eligible to be a system event and what is not. It is the level of the basal self-instruction of the system by a binary code, by a strictly two-valued distinction, which is in a certain sense nihilistic, insofar as it is an in-itself distinction, a (in Spencer-Brown's terminology) continented distinction, in which every reference to one side negates the other side, but, as one might say with Hegel, in the form of a certain negation, thus not in the form of an erasure. In this way, a smooth switching back and forth between the code sides is possible, and: the exclusion of world ballast, that is, that which otherwise occurs in the world that endures the incision of the code, for example: morality. The code is extremely poor in the world, it does not offer 'rich' directives. But it is precisely this ruthlessness that gives rise to its power. Well-known examples are right/wrong (law), have/have-not (economy), immanence/transcendence (religion), true/not true (science)."
